    "source": "scripts/gen-perf-data.sh",
    "note": "Public testimages/ only. Each figure is the p50 over the measured iterations, decomposed into four stages: response (dense response map), detection (threshold + non-maximum suppression + cluster filter; for Radon this also runs the 3-point Gaussian peak fit, its only subpixel step), refinement (image-domain subpixel), and orientation (two-axis fit + descriptor assembly). total_ms is the sum of the four stage p50s; throughput is whole-pipeline megapixels per second. Per image we measure a matrix: ChESS over refiner {center_of_mass, forstner, saddle_point} x orientation {ring_fit, disk_fit, off}, and Radon over refiner {radon_peak, center_of_mass} x orientation {ring_fit, disk_fit, off}. The orientation=off rows isolate the per-corner orientation cost, which is the single largest stage on corner-dense frames. ChESS reads the threshold as an absolute response floor (default 30) and Radon as a fraction of the per-frame maximum (default 0.30); the two response scores are defined on different scales, so the detectors' corner counts are not directly comparable. The Radon strategy's image-domain refinement is a no-op, so its refinement stage reads zero and the two Radon refiner rows are identical. Built with the simd feature, single-threaded.",
    "matrix_note": "Compare the orientation column across ring_fit / disk_fit / off to read the per-corner orientation cost, and across ChESS / Radon to compare detectors. Refiner and orientation method do not visibly move corners, so a single overlay per detector (default refiner + ring_fit) is shown."
